  "prompt": "What is the difference between Dijon mustard and other mustards?",
  "response": "Dijon mustard is a specific type of mustard that originates from the city of Dijon in France. It is typically made from brown or black mustard seeds, white wine, and a variety of spices and flavorings, such as garlic or herbs. The use of white wine in the preparation of Dijon mustard gives it a unique, tangy flavor that sets it apart from other mustards.\n\nOther types of mustard can vary significantly in terms of their ingredients and flavor profiles. For example, yellow mustard, which is commonly used in the United States, is made from yellow mustard seeds, vinegar, and turmeric, which gives it its characteristic bright yellow color. It has a milder, less tangy flavor than Dijon mustard.\n\nOther popular types of mustard include honey mustard, which is made with honey and has a sweet flavor; whole grain mustard, which is made with whole mustard seeds and has a coarse texture; and spicy brown mustard, which is made with brown mustard seeds and has a spicier flavor.\n\nOverall, the main difference between Dijon mustard and other mustards is the ingredients used and the resulting flavor profile, with Dijon mustard having a unique tanginess from the use of white wine in its preparation.",
